post_text:
Just a quick reminder as we welcome students back to the building any students that may have a medical need (i.e. inhaler, medication, EpiPen) parents will need to complete the appropriate forms. Any new students and/or 6th graders will also need to provide an updated or current immunization record. For 6th grade students, T-dap is a required Immunization even if under the age of 11 when entering 6th grade. If you choose not to have your student vaccinated according to the ACIP schedule for personal or religious reasons you must submit a non-medical exemption. These forms must be submitted on a yearly basis. All health forms can be found on the Health Services page on the District website or at the link below.

http://gilpin.k12.co.us/district_services/health_services

post_text:
Dear Gilpin School Community,

Our current timeline is to review the pandemic and make a decision on September 1, 2020 about how we will proceed with teaching and learning. The decision will be one of the following options:

continue with 100% Remote Learning Program or
change to a 25%/75% Hybrid Learning Program or
change to a 100% In-person Learning Program

If a decision is made to change the current learning plan, the implementation of the new plan will begin on September 8, 2020. The Gilpin Online Learning program through CDLS/Edentum stays in place for the entire school year.

The September 1 decision needs parent input and the important data you provide via the survey will be considered for the learning program decision-making. Complete the survey by August 26 or as soon as possible.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdZ9WnvVKi-8Q6WehomODJaUF3ugYT2u5j3hIleT0rG3QfDzw/viewform?gxids=7757

Does your child receive free or reduced-price school meals during the school year, or do you believe you may now qualify based on a recent income change during the months of March, April, and May 2020? Pandemic-EBT, or P-EBT, can help you feed your family. You will receive a card with approximately $279 per eligible child that you can use to purchase food at stores that accept EBT. If you already receive SNAP benefits and are eligible for P-EBT, these funds will automatically load into your existing account. If you do not currently receive SNAP benefits, apply here for P-EBT today:
https://www.colorado.gov/cdhs/p-ebt

For more information click the link below to view the parent letter that was emailed to families.

http://gilpin.k12.co.us/UserFiles/Servers/Server_73445/File/District%20Services/Food%20&%20Nutrition%20Services/20.21%20Information/P-EBT%20Letter%20to%20Parents.pdf

post_text:
GCSD Transitions to New Student Information System (SIS)

Prior to COVID-19, GCSD began the process to transition from Infinite Campus (IC) to the new Student Information System (SIS) Alma. IC is no longer accessible. The change to the Alma SIS is because Alma will support teaching and learning better. Alma is compatible with our Google Classroom Learning Management System (LMS).

Parents/Guardians should have received an email earlier today with log-in information. If you didn't receive an email please check your spam folder and allow the Alma address. If you have any questions or need assistance please call Gretchen, Joni or Catrina.

Congratulation Class of 2020!

Alyssa Webb

"Alyssa we are so very proud of you and who you have become. You have grown up so fast and surprised us every step of the way. We are very excited to see what you do next."

Alyssa has attended Gilpin County School since kindergarten. She has encountered many things along the way. She had tried different things like basketball, cheerleading, soccer, and the play. Her dreams of what she wanted to do in life have changed a few times from a Veterinarian to an Actress and now the Medical Field. She is so amazingly smart and we know that she will be amazing at everything she does. Alyssa was a lifeguard for the Gilpin County Rec Center for almost two years. Alyssa plans to attend Red Rocks Community College, then transfer to CU Boulder. She plans to study Pre-Med and then go to Medical School to become an Anesthesiologist. Alyssa says " my time at Gilpin County wasn't always the greatest but I feel it has prepared me for my future."

post_text:
Congratulations Class of 2020!

Hello everyone! My name is John Paul DiMauro. I have kept very busy during my high school years. I have really enjoyed exploring the arts via the plays our amazing school has put on over the last multiple years. I have been a behind the scenes assistant and enjoyed enriching my life with all the experiences and person to person interactions this has allowed me.

I have also participated in baseball and football during my 4 years at Gilpin. The friendships and team bonding are things I will take with me into my future and will never forget. I started Warren Tech at Red Rocks for autobody work while still in high school and very much appreciate that opportunity provided by our school.

After high school, I plan to continue with that line of training to eventually obtain a job in the same field. Gilpin has successfully provided me with the tools I need to become successful as I move forward in life. Thank you to all my teachers and family for supporting me and pushing me to be my best.

post_text:
Due to current circumstances, our students were not able to have a Prom or After Prom this year. Missing out on an essential social event like this can be hard, especially as a senior. We wanted to help make it up to our seniors by allowing them the opportunity to still receive After Prom gifts. We held an unconventional gift give away via a webex video call where we randomly selected senior names out of one bag and numbers out of another bag, each correlating to a gift. Although we know this does not make up for missing a crucial time of their high school careers, it was a reminder of the care and support the community has for these seniors. Without the generous donations of our Gilpin County Commissioners, these gifts would not have been possible. We hope this helped provide our seniors with a sense of normalcy even if just for a few brief moments.

-Thank you Gilpin County Boosters-

Gilpin County Booster Club

post_text:
Congratulations Class of 2020!

Noelle Arrington is excited and relieved to have finished her senior year relatively unscathed, after what turned out to be a challenging year at a completely new school. It's not something she recommends, but she is grateful for the chance to face her fears head-on and overcome them. She would like to thank the teachers and fellow students who helped her to feel included and accepted into this amazing and tight-knit community.

Noelle will be attending the University of Utah in the Fall (though possibly taking a gap year to explore the world first), and will be studying her lifelong love of Video Game Design, with a minor in Animation Studies. Noelle has always been a determined and dedicated student, multi-talented in the areas of music, art, science, and engineering, and we wish her luck and success in her future endeavors. We love you Noelle!!

post_text:
Congratulations Class of 2020!

Jake Marshall

From the time that you were a tiny baby that I could hold in one hand, to the kid that played in there creek, to the young man I see today-

I AM SO PROUD TO BE YOUR FATHER!!

I am so happy to see you getting ready to start your own adventures in life and make your way!

My advice:

Life is fast, don't wait for others!

Follow your dreams now!

Be brave, try new things, go new places.

You can never have too many friends or Jeeps!😉

Love with all your heart when you find the right person.

Never let negative people drag you down.

Always carry a pocket knife.

Work hard and find a job you love.

And MOST important-

Make time to hug your parents!!

❤- Dad

Logan Prewitt

I have truly enjoyed my time at Gilpin. I have been blessed to be at Gilpin since preschool.

Noemi Correa

I will be attending the University of Northern Colorado and majoring in pre-med. I hope to become an orthopedic surgeon in the near future. I’m really excited to go on and further my education and be able to experience college life and be on my own for a bit.

I will definitely miss being a part of the team and most of all I will miss having all my friends in the same place at once. I’m extremely grateful for all my coaches during high school, they always motivated me to do my best whether it was on the court or off the court. I would also like to thank my teachers for helping me throughout my academic career.

post_text:
Congratulations Class of 2020!

Nicole Adams

While at Gilpin I participated in volleyball, basketball, and track all four years of school (if you count the beginning of the season).

Outside of school, I am usually pretty busy working as a lifeguard and seasonal sports official at the Gilpin County rec center. I have valued my involvement in athletics the most out of my four years because of the friendships and memories that were made and I will carry with me. My other hobbies in my free time include camping with my family and traveling.

I will be attending the University of Nebraska-Lincoln next fall as a Ruth Leverton scholar. I will be studying business administration and marketing. While I am not sure what I “want to be” yet I know my areas of study will open many doors for me and my interests of leadership, networking, and creativity. I am so excited to be involved in the UNL community and am most excited for the Husker gamedays!

Congratulations Class of 2020!

Joyce has had a busy four years of high school. She has been on the honor roll many times, completed a Fire Science course and is currently completing the Power Equipment and Motorcycle Technology course at Warren Tech.

She has played basketball for 4 years, wrestling 1 year, baseball 1 year and was a manager for the football team for 2 years. Outside of school, Joyce has excelled in Taekwondo, loves riding her dirt bike and working on vehicles with her dad. She is a member of the Christian Motorcycle Association.

Her dream is to join the Airforce and become a Fire Protection Specialist. Her back up plan is to get a degree in Fire Science and become a Firefighter. We are so proud of her! Congratulations Joyce! Follow your dreams!

post_text:
March 27, 2020
Dear Gilpin School Community,
Governor Jared Polis issued a Stay At Home order on March 25. However, schools are exempt when providing essential services: “K-12 public and private schools for the purpose of providing meals, housing, facilitating or providing materials for distance learning, and providing other essential services to students.”

To facilitate essential services for students to participate in distance (remote) learning, we will provide families the opportunity to come to the school to pick up any items they may have left at the school such as supplies, medication, and technology on Monday, March 30, 2020, from 8 a.m. to 12 noon. Contact Mr. Rothenberger if you have a Chromebook issue, arothenberger@gilpin.k12.co.us

To view the full letter click the link below.

https://bit.ly/2xzOkOP

Gilpin County Sheriff's Office
Gilpin OEM

On Monday, March 16, 2020, we will provide families the opportunity to come to the school to pick up any items they may have left at the school such as supplies, medication, and technology from 7:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.

Please access your email for more detailed information about the Remote Learning Plan for students. Check in your spam folder for this email

post_text:
Gilpin School Community,

The District received an anonymous and unsubstantiated Safe2Tell report this morning around 10 a.m. that a student may have brought a gun to school today, December 16, 2019. An investigation into the anonymous Safe2Tell tip began immediately. Additional Gilpin County Sheriff’s Deputies responded to the school for additional safety and security.

At approximately 11 a.m. a “Hold! In your classroom. Clear the halls” was announced to students and staff. School staff began the process to search lockers, backpacks, and bags in the school. A visual inspection of all vehicles parked on campus was conducted. Lunch periods were delayed for about 15 minutes.

The search concluded just after 12 p.m. and no weapon was found at the school.

All concerns for student and staff safety are taken seriously.

Students and staff have resumed the regular class schedule. School will continue until the 4 p.m. dismissal today, December 16, 2019.

post_text:
Gilpin School Community,

The Gilpin County Sheriff notified the school at approximately 8:10 a.m. today, May 20, 2019, that they received a report that a transient walking southbound on Highway 119 toward the school entrance was caring a weapon.

The school immediately went on “Lockout!” A Lockout! secures the perimeter. All exterior doors were checked to be sure the doors were locked. Teachers brought students from outside to inside. Students and staff continued to conduct school business as usual.

The individual was detained by Gilpin County Sheriff’s Deputies on Highway 119 at the school entrance. The individual possessed an air soft pellet rifle. The individual was investigated and has been transported out of the area.

The Sheriff lifted the “Lockout!” at 8:20 a.m. Students and staff were notified and school continues as normally scheduled.

post_text:
Gilpin School Community,
Good Morning. In collaboration with other Denver-metro area school districts, Gilpin County School will be closed on Wednesday, April 17, 2019, due to the credible safety threat to school students and staff. Sol Pais, the alleged perpetrator of this threat to school safety, was last seen in the Bergen Park area on Squaw Pass Road yesterday.
High School student participation in World Language Day is cancelled for April 17.
A decision about whether after school activities for April 17 will be held will be made by 1 p.m. today and communicated to families via email.
Additional updates about this threat to school safety will be sent to families as the situation warrants or when new information becomes available.
Repeating. In collaboration with other Denver-metro area school districts, Gilpin County School will be closed on Wednesday, April 17, 2019, due to the credible safety threat to school students and staff.
